through all of these that you see on the screen here, but they fall into four different categories.

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:18.719
The first of which is data organization. These are things that I imagine are familiar to many of you,

00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:25.679
like storing our data in tidy data tables and storing our data in a managed system of record.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:34.479
Another category here is the data analysis, where we want to separate out our data storage

00:11:34.479 --> 00:11:40.400
and our analysis workflows. And we also want to create some transparency in terms of how we

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:46.000
analyze our data. This is looking at things like Git-based version control to ensure that we have

00:11:46.799 --> 00:11:54.080
good reproducibility and reliability on these methods. Third is data access. This is a particular

00:11:54.239 --> 00:11:59.119
challenge for much of our research where we're using often proprietary data formats. This is

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:02.799
where we want to make sure that we can store data in a way that's going to be accessible for the

00:12:02.799 --> 00:12:07.679
long term. We can have organized data, but it needs to be both organized and accessible in

00:12:07.679 --> 00:12:12.880
order for us to have that durable value out of that. And then in particular, looking for long-term

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:21.440
