00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:53.680
amount of time working on this project, so it's worth the upfront investment to make sure that

00:21:53.680 --> 00:22:01.280
it's one that really makes sense for your workflows. Thinking about who could participate,

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:09.359
who would be a good candidate for Academy? The number one predictor of success in our experience

00:22:09.359 --> 00:22:14.719
is intrinsic motivation. That might sound somewhat obvious, but you need to want to do this.

00:22:15.439 --> 00:22:20.560
You need to really care if you are learning the content within Academy.

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:25.119
Secondly, a good candidate will have a project that they can go and apply the knowledge that

00:22:25.119 --> 00:22:31.199
they're learning right away. Ideally, they could do it in parallel as they're learning the key

00:22:31.199 --> 00:22:38.319
concepts within Academy. And third, you need to have both the time and support in order to

00:22:38.319 --> 00:22:44.239
participate. Practically, you probably want to make sure that your manager, your boss,

00:22:44.239 --> 00:22:49.599
whomever, supports this program and wants to make sure that you can dedicate time at work

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:56.000
during working hours to invest in upskilling yourself through the Academy curriculum.

00:23:00.319 --> 00:23:06.239
All right, so on the flip side of that, who might be a bad candidate? Who probably should not

00:23:06.239 --> 00:23:10.959
participate in Academy? Now, there's lots of examples that I could think of here,

00:23:11.520 --> 00:23:16.959
but I wanted to highlight a couple that you might not think about. Number one,

00:23:17.439 --> 00:23:27.839
number one, you're an experienced R user. We had a number of people say that they knew R,

00:23:27.839 --> 00:23:36.239
but what they were looking for was wanting to do it the right way. I can say that from experience

00:23:36.239 --> 00:23:41.920
here, that probably means that you either are too knowledgeable to participate compared to the other

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:47.520
members of your cohort, or you don't really have enough of that intrinsic motivation.

00:23:48.079 --> 00:23:53.439
You're not necessarily learning a particular set of the right way to do things, rather than

00:23:53.439 --> 00:23:59.599
learning maybe some best practices that you can apply with your peers. Also, thinking of this

00:23:59.599 --> 00:24:05.040
experience here, if you've already regularly are building and deploying Shiny apps, probably too

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:11.520
advanced. If you're a regular contributor to Tidy Tuesday on Twitter, again, probably too advanced.

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:18.160
Maybe the number one giveaway, if you are able to successfully achieve writing some new Tidy

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:23.760
evaluation code, and you don't have to go look on the RStudio community or go through the docs,

00:24:23.760 --> 00:24:32.319
yeah, you're definitely too advanced for Academy. The other category to look out for here is people

00:24:32.319 --> 00:24:37.760
who are excited about learning how to code, but they're just thinking of it as a new skill.

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:45.920
We had a survey that we sent out before our initial cohorts with Academy to get some sense

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:50.560
of the community of why they wanted to participate. We had a number of different answers along the

00:24:50.560 --> 00:25:00.800
lines of, yeah, I think this would be great for a skill to add to my list. You probably don't want

00:25:00.800 --> 00:25:06.160
to select those people for RStudio Academy, predominantly because they don't have enough

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:12.880
of that intrinsic motivation to want to go and complete the curriculum and then apply it to

00:25:12.880 --> 00:25:16.880
their work. The other thing to look out for is if you don't have a project to apply it to,

00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:21.359
it's likely that the skills that you learn, if you don't maintain that habit, if you're not

00:25:21.359 --> 00:25:25.760
developing this as a continuous practice, you're probably not going to have that good of an

00:25:25.760 --> 00:25:34.319
experience. Okay, enough of the negatives. What makes a good cohort? I mentioned that a cohort

00:25:34.319 --> 00:25:42.079
needs to have somewhere between five and seven people in it. And Dow is a very large company.

00:25:42.079 --> 00:25:47.040
We have around 36,000 employees. I mentioned a few thousand within our R&D groups spread

00:25:47.040 --> 00:25:54.640
across the globe. This made picking our cohorts a bit of a challenge. What we've learned from this,

00:25:54.640 --> 00:26:00.640
we've had several now, is the components that make a good cohort are, number one,

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:06.079
the people are from a similar work group. It doesn't have to literally be the same thing that

00:26:06.079 --> 00:26:12.400
people have the identical roles. In fact, we've found some good outcomes from having people at

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:17.280
maybe some of our highest level of technical leadership roles and some people at the various,

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:20.800
the earliest entrance into the company. Those seem to work okay together.

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:26.160
What is more important is that the types of problems that they're thinking about

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:30.959
on a daily basis are similar enough that they can discuss with how they could apply the new

00:26:30.959 --> 00:26:38.079
skills that they're learning to their own work. Now, again, a nuts and bolts component here is

00:26:38.079 --> 00:26:42.719
you want to make sure that you have a similar time zone. You don't want people struggling to

00:26:42.719 --> 00:26:48.880
attend the group sessions. Those are critical to success, as we've heard from our participants.

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:53.439
And then the third piece here, something that we sort of learned the hard way,

00:26:53.439 --> 00:26:59.599
of making sure that everybody within a given cohort is of a similar skill level. I had that

00:26:59.599 --> 00:27:05.040
long list of identifiers that might suggest that somebody is too skilled for academy.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:10.079
You want to make sure that if you do have somebody with advanced skills participating, that

00:27:10.079 --> 00:27:14.640
they're well matched with people who are at least close to their skill level. You probably don't

00:27:14.640 --> 00:27:19.920
want a brand new beginner with somebody who's regularly deploying shiny apps, for example.

00:27:20.719 --> 00:27:26.800
Okay, so let's talk about what people thought of this. We surveyed our first cohort, where we had

00:27:26.800 --> 00:27:33.599
about 19 people participate, to see what their experience was like. I have two quotes that I

00:27:33.599 --> 00:27:39.119
pulled out from the survey here. The first one is talking about the fantastic user experience they

00:27:39.119 --> 00:27:45.199
had, really enjoying the bite-sized learning messages that they got from the lessons themselves.

00:27:45.199 --> 00:27:50.479
And the second one, which was particularly encouraging to us, was hearing how highly they

00:27:50.479 --> 00:27:55.359
recommended this program for other researchers within our company to go and apply to their own

00:27:55.359 --> 00:28:01.520
work as well. This also gives some hopefully helpful markers in terms of the time commitment

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:07.920
that you should expect. The guidance that we gave in advance was to spend about 30 minutes a day

00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:15.280
on the curriculum, not including the group sessions, so maybe adding an additional hour to

00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:20.239
that. You can see from the learners that we surveyed that most people were spending between

00:28:20.239 --> 00:28:26.800
three and ten hours per week on Academy. A few learners were spending more than ten hours,

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:32.000
and a few maybe were a bit too advanced, spending less than three hours per week on the content.

00:28:33.359 --> 00:28:35.920
We also surveyed them about whether they thought it was a good idea to do this,

00:28:35.920 --> 00:28:39.280
we also surveyed them about whether they thought it was a good use of their time,

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:43.359
if they recommended it to others, if we should invest more money into this,

00:28:43.359 --> 00:28:48.640
and the criticality of the mentors to this. Now, these might be a little bit difficult to read,

00:28:48.640 --> 00:28:52.959
but pretty much everybody said that they either agreed and strongly agreed with a few being

00:28:52.959 --> 00:28:58.719
neutral. But overall, what we saw was quite positive feedback. Maybe the most important

00:28:58.719 --> 00:29:05.040
metric from this was, are they still using the content that they've learned? Surveying them

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:11.119
six months after they left Academy, we found that 16 out of the 17 of the survey respondents

00:29:11.680 --> 00:29:19.280
were still writing code at least once per month, or more frequently. The one person out of the 17

00:29:19.280 --> 00:29:26.000
who isn't, let me know that she took a new role that was as more or less a data science manager,

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:31.280
and so she wasn't writing code on a regular basis, but was still applying what she learned

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:35.199
every single day, and in fact, more so than when she first started the program.

00:29:36.479 --> 00:29:41.839
We were blown away by this feedback, and it really encouraged us as we started to shape out future

00:29:41.839 --> 00:29:49.040
cohorts. I will admit that we probably had a bias in the amount of enthusiasm of our initial

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:54.719
participants, so I don't think we'll have quite the same level of positive feedback as we survey

00:29:54.719 --> 00:30:00.000
future cohorts, but I do anticipate that we're going to continue to see really positive outcomes

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:02.719
from our participants and Academy overall.

00:30:07.199 --> 00:30:13.680
One point that we're still working on today is, what do we do with people after they graduate

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:18.560
from Academy? Academy, at least for our curriculum, and it will be different for

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:23.760
yours for sure, but we didn't focus too much on reproducibility and deployment,

00:30:24.239 --> 00:30:31.119
but sharing your analyses, as I mentioned for the criterion for our workbench, the ability to

00:30:31.119 --> 00:30:36.640
share what you're creating, share your insights, that's really where all the value resides.

00:30:37.839 --> 00:30:42.640
So, looking at some future developments for our own internal efforts after Academy,

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:46.719
we are wanting to find ways to offer more advanced lessons.

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:53.680
I will give a bit of a challenge here, which is creating some of the more advanced lessons

00:30:54.479 --> 00:31:00.160
is a bit of a challenge in that we can't look to RStudio for as much help here, because

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:06.000
most of the specifics are actually something that is related to us as a company, not necessarily to

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:13.280
a generic data science concept. We also have a focus on transferring people from the Academy

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:19.839
environment onto our local workbench, where they can go and apply that to our most sensitive or

00:31:19.839 --> 00:31:28.640
internal data. There certainly was some work going on alongside the participation in Academy,

00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:33.760
where people were using our on-premises capabilities, but smoothing that transition

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:38.400
is something that we could work on in the future. And then the last piece is focused on

00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:44.479
community building. Now that we have more and more people that are able to participate in

00:31:44.479 --> 00:31:50.239
Academy, we want to have a landing zone for them to come and continue to learn from others. We

00:31:50.239 --> 00:31:53.599
have heard a number of times that people miss Academy, they wish that it could have gone on

00:31:53.599 --> 00:31:59.520
longer, and that community building is a critical piece to ensure that people have that same

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:07.359
positive spirit that they can apply their data science skills continuously. I want to close here

00:32:07.359 --> 00:32:12.640
by telling a little bit of a story that came out of Academy, which is one of our success stories of

00:32:12.640 --> 00:32:19.599
what an Academy participant was able to create with a little bit of additional effort. She got

00:32:19.599 --> 00:32:25.119
particularly excited about the capabilities that she was building, but this is an Academy graduate

00:32:25.119 --> 00:32:32.000
who did not have prior experience with our prior to this experience and what they were able to go

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:39.439
and create. This requires a little bit of understanding of the sort of work that this was

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:47.119
intending to address. So, in particular, the need here was that there was a piece of equipment that

00:32:47.119 --> 00:32:52.959
was used for analyzing some of our products, particularly its polymer analysis tool,

00:32:53.760 --> 00:32:58.800
where users could come up and use this instrumentation and collect their own data.

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:03.920
A benefit of this is that they don't have to rely on subject matter experts to go collect this,

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:09.680
but there was a gap in that people were unable to go and analyze their data without advanced

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:17.119
training. As a solution to this, a Shiny app was built that allowed the user to come and to

00:33:17.119 --> 00:33:22.959
analyze using enough subject matter expertise that was not encoded in one-on-one mentoring.

00:33:22.959 --> 00:33:31.119
Instead, it was encoded in code, where you could go and apply that code to analyze the data

00:33:31.119 --> 00:33:37.119
and extract those valuable insights. The app itself had a number of different components,

00:33:37.119 --> 00:33:41.760
such as selecting and plotting data, analyzing that data, automatic report generation,

00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:47.040
viewing of historical data, and then an ability to go and inspect calibration

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:52.160
curves to ensure that the results were, in fact, of value.

00:33:53.520 --> 00:34:00.079
Now, I will say that this was not solely the Academy participant's effort in contributing to

00:34:00.079 --> 00:34:05.760
this, but she is a very valuable and active contributor to this capability and is currently

00:34:06.479 --> 00:34:13.679
becoming the predominant maintainer of this codebase. So, Academy empowered her to be able

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:19.919
to continue to learn, tackle new code, tackle new packages, and be able to apply that to a

00:34:21.199 --> 00:34:26.800
tool that is creating an improved employee experience for both the developers of the

00:34:26.800 --> 00:34:30.800
tool themselves, they don't have to spend as much time coaching people on data analysis,

00:34:30.800 --> 00:34:36.239
and also for the end users of the Shiny app, where they can have a much streamlined

00:34:36.239 --> 00:34:40.399
approach and are no longer reliant on others to extracting insights from their data.

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:48.639
The last thing I want to say here is a huge acknowledgement to many of the people that

00:34:48.639 --> 00:34:55.679
made this successful Academy partnership possible. I want to give a particular shout out to Tony

00:34:55.679 --> 00:35:00.320
Sokolov. I saw him in the chat here, so I know that he's watching along with me. A huge thanks

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:06.239
to both Dow and RStudio mentors for all the work that they put in to make this program a success.

00:35:06.959 --> 00:35:11.439
And I want to thank all of you for giving me the opportunity to speak about this today,

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:16.719
and I'd be very happy to take any questions that people have about our own Academy experience or

00:35:16.719 --> 00:35:20.399
about the questions you might have for your own. So, thank you very much.

00:35:23.679 --> 00:35:29.120
Thank you so much, James. That was great. We're all clapping, even though you can't hear us right

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:36.800
now. I see there's quite a few questions coming in right now, so let me organize myself here.

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:43.040
But just a reminder to everybody that you can ask questions on YouTube Live, if you're watching

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:49.520
there, or on LinkedIn, if you're watching there. And if you want to ask questions anonymously,

00:35:49.520 --> 00:35:53.840
you can do so as well. I just put the link there on the screen.

00:35:55.280 --> 00:36:04.639
But I see Laura asked a great question over on Slido, and it was, would be fun to learn.

00:36:04.719 --> 00:36:08.560
How do you handle those that know coding would be useful to them,

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:12.959
but can't motivate to take five steps back to take 10 steps forward?

00:36:15.040 --> 00:36:20.000
Yeah, that's probably our toughest use case. But typically what we'll do in that case,

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:25.120
because we have a somewhat large base of researchers, we typically will pair them

00:36:25.120 --> 00:36:30.719
with somebody who might have that capability, where you could accelerate their individual

00:36:30.719 --> 00:36:36.639
project work. So you pair somebody like an RStudio Academy graduate, and have them work

00:36:36.639 --> 00:36:44.000
side by side on potentially going and doing the actual project itself. But if it's the situation

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:50.080
where they predominantly want to learn these capabilities themselves, if it's somebody who

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:55.040
really just wants to learn that, but doesn't have a use case right away, our recommendation in that

00:36:55.040 --> 00:37:00.159
case is to have them go and take advantage of the free online resources that all of us, I'm sure,

00:37:00.159 --> 00:37:06.320
are familiar with. So I think it's probably an unsatisfactory answer. I know that I would

00:37:06.320 --> 00:37:11.120
probably be unsatisfied if I got that from my survey response that I filled out. But it's really

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:16.639
a question of, again, that intrinsic motivation. If they're not excited to learn the content,

00:37:17.439 --> 00:37:20.800
we think that there might be other opportunities for them to go and learn that instead.

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:31.199
I guess one thing I will add as well is, if it's a time issue, we did spend a good bit of effort to

00:37:31.199 --> 00:37:36.800
convince leadership, our internal leadership, of the value of these sorts of skill sets. So having

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:45.280
a base of projects that have already created value from this is a really good argument, I think, for

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:54.080
dedicating the time. Awesome. I'll try to be better about showing these on the screen right

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:59.919
away. Here we go. Penny asked a question, how can more advanced users participate in developing

00:37:59.919 --> 00:38:08.320
curriculums? Yeah, that's a great question. What we have done is we, a group of us, it was

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:13.760
predominantly Tony, I should say, was heavily involved in developing the curriculum for our

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:19.040
learners. So it was a curriculum that was based off a real data set that was sanitized and

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:24.000
anonymized in a way that would allow us to release it externally. So what I would look for, for the

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:29.760
more advanced users, is to identify use cases where you have a good data set that might be

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:36.959
representative of what other people could see. I also would encourage anybody who has the skill

00:38:36.959 --> 00:38:42.080
set, is already familiar with a shiny app development, to go and try to create some

00:38:42.080 --> 00:38:48.479
modules of yourself. The caveat I would give there is that there has been tremendous thought

00:38:48.479 --> 00:38:54.800
into developing the academy curriculum overall. Don't let your leadership convince you

00:38:54.800 --> 00:39:00.560
that you don't need this, that you can just do it yourself. It's a fantastic curriculum and I would

00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:04.639
encourage you to try to take advantage of that rather than try to roll your own. For the more

00:39:04.639 --> 00:39:10.959
advanced content, maybe take advantage of some publishing capabilities like maybe a

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:15.760
R Markdown-based website or maybe a Corto-based website if you have some early adapters out there,

00:39:16.399 --> 00:39:22.159
where you can go and create some interactive or at least some simple websites that you could

00:39:22.159 --> 00:39:31.040
publish for others to go and take advantage of. Great, thank you. Another question over from

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:36.879
YouTube is, does academy also teach good coding style and version control?

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:44.479
The absolute curriculum, like the particular curriculum that you'll see, will be based off of

00:39:44.479 --> 00:39:51.040
your own desires. So if you have a strong desire to include Git-based version control, that is

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:56.879
certainly something that can happen. It was not covered in ours in favor of other topics. There's

00:39:56.879 --> 00:40:04.159
a lot to cover in 12 weeks. We wish we had more. The coding style will come out of all of the

00:40:04.159 --> 00:40:09.919
tutorials are written and following, I assume, the TidyVerse style guide. That's just how I learned,

00:40:09.919 --> 00:40:17.280
so I don't know anything else from that. But you can select amongst the list of topics

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:21.040
whatever is important for the participants in the individual session.

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:30.399
Thank you. Someone had asked on Slido anonymously, if you're trying to sell academy to the individual

00:40:30.399 --> 00:40:35.439
who would fill the group mentor role, what level of commitment and bandwidth do they need to have?

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:46.479
So I'm actively trying to sell that role as we're shaping future cohorts. The most significant piece

00:40:47.439 --> 00:40:53.840
there is the skill set that you need to have is a familiarity with how data science is done

00:40:53.840 --> 00:41:02.080
at your organization. You don't have to, for example, be an expert in R. We have some experts

00:41:02.080 --> 00:41:07.760
in Python who have already participated as mentors. And in terms of effort, you need to have,

00:41:07.760 --> 00:41:12.560
I would say, about three hours a week that you could dedicate. The first hour would be attending

00:41:12.639 --> 00:41:18.959
the group sessions. The second hour would be attending an open office hours period, which

00:41:19.919 --> 00:41:25.040
is somewhat optional, but I would encourage a mentor to attend. And the third is being able

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:30.080
to answer questions sort of as an ad hoc basis. Now, I would say that three hours a week is

00:41:30.080 --> 00:41:38.239
probably the floor. I would encourage a mentor to dedicate at least a half a day, if not more.

00:41:38.239 --> 00:41:42.639
And what likely will come out of this is some projects worked where you can work one-on-one

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:46.479
with some of the participants to translate what they're learning.

00:41:46.479 --> 00:41:51.040
And you'll see opportunities where you could streamline some of their code where

00:41:51.040 --> 00:41:56.000
if they haven't really gotten deep into dplyr yet, and you can see a way to have a streamlined

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:59.280
pipeline, that's something that would take a little bit more effort, but I think it would

00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:06.479
be worth it to accelerate some of the learning. Thank you. Thanks for letting us through all

00:42:06.479 --> 00:42:15.199
these questions at you too, James. There's a lot of great ones coming in. Someone just asked,

00:42:15.199 --> 00:42:20.080
is the type of data you work with relevant to the work you do at Dow, or is it random

00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:25.679
data sets regardless of which company you're with? For our use case, it was literally data from a

00:42:25.679 --> 00:42:30.639
project. It was not a successful project, but it was a real project. So it was as real as we can

00:42:30.639 --> 00:42:38.399
get in terms of the data. We did simplify it a small bit to not intimidate people too much

00:42:38.399 --> 00:42:43.840
from some of the volume or maybe the messiness of the data, but it's as real as we could get

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:49.600
and still let sort of people outside of the company see it as well.

00:42:52.479 --> 00:42:59.840
That's awesome. So somebody else asked, what other ways of teaching R have you tried or considered

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:08.080
at Dow, and how does Academy compare? I can speak from my own experience in what is not the

00:43:08.080 --> 00:43:16.959
right way to do it. I try to organize a local section amongst my technology area of having

00:43:16.959 --> 00:43:22.959
meetings every couple of weeks where we would cover maybe a chapter or two of R for Data Science.

00:43:22.959 --> 00:43:28.320
I imagine a book that many of you are familiar with. What I found was that people were able to

00:43:28.320 --> 00:43:37.120
quite easily answer or complete the challenges throughout those chapters. What was missing

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:42.479
there was the actual community building and the practice. So people were able to hear me talk about

